          "thinking": "Let me implement the currency converter module based on the spec.\n\nKey requirements:\n1. `createConverter(rates, maxAgeMs?)` returns `{ convert, addRate }`\n2. Support inverse rates (if A→B exists, B→A = 1/rate)\n3. Support transitive conversion (A→B→C via BFS/Dijkstra)\n4. Staleness detection (reject rates older than maxAgeMs)\n5. Same currency → rate=1, amount unchanged\n6. Amounts rounded to 2 decimal places\n7. Return `ConversionResult { amount, rate, path }`\n\n\n8. I'll store rates in a map and use BFS to find conversion paths, checking staleness along the way and computing composite rates across the path. For inverse rates, I'll derive B→A = 1/rate with the same timestamp, and the path should be an array of currencies traversed during conversion.\n\nNow I'm setting up the converter with a rate map structure...\n\nBuilding the conversion effect... Writing the BFS traversal...\n\nNow I'm wrapping this in an Effect to handle errors, then exposing a synchronous `convert` function that runs the effect and throws if conversion fails. The `addRate` method just loads new rates into the graph, and since `addEdge` overwrites duplicates, updating existing rates works automatically.\n\nFor the `rate` field in the result, I need to make sure it represents the actual exchange rate used in the conversion path. The round-trip test should work fine with inverse rates. I also need to round amounts to 2 decimal places as the spec requires.\n\nOn validation, the spec doesn't explicitly call for rejecting negative amounts, so I'll skip that unless tests indicate otherwise. But I do need to handle the stale rate case properly—if all possible paths only use rates beyond the `maxAgeMs` threshold, that should throw an error.\n\nNow I'm checking what needs to be exported: the `createConverter` function definitely, and probably the `Rate` and `ConversionResult` interfaces too so users can type their data properly.\n\nOne thing I want to verify: when I load a rate and add both directional edges (A→B and B→A), they share the same timestamp, so staleness is consistent in both directions. That should be correct.\n\nThe instructions specify using Effect internally for composition and error handling while exporting plain TypeScript interfaces, so I'll keep that approach and write out the final implementation.",
